A few weeks back, Cam and I got our cross country skis out on a bright sunny morning and made our way five kilometres along the snowy road to our neighbour’s house to watch the Gold Medal hockey game. It seems funny to me that our ‘neighbours’ live that far away, but when there are give or take 25 people sharing a small island together for the winter, then everybody is your neighbour. It’s been about three and a half months since the last ferry and a little longer than that since we last stepped off the island. The island road, end to end is about eight kilometres. I used to cycle 10 kilometres to work most days in London - from Hackney to Marylebone - cycling past some of the busiest and coolest spots in the whole city. It’s very strange to think just how much my local environment has changed since then. To put that into perspective, Cam I like think about just how much more densely populated our London neighbourhood was in comparison to our new abode. Pictou Island has an area of roughly 12.8 square kilometres and right now, around 25 residents. That’s about two people per square kilometre. The UK has a population density of 285 people per square kilometre and that’s not even considering that 70% of the UK is agricultural, and therefore not residential, land - a statistic that continually blows my mind. If you take that into account, a rough back of the envelope calculation means the population density jumps to 950/km^2. England is more densely populated on average than the rest of the UK with 450 people per square kilometre (or 1400/km^2 if you look at the 32% of land that isn’t agricultural), and then zooming into central London, the Borough of Hackney has around 14,000 residents per square kilometre. Surprisingly Pictou Island is about 70% of the size of Hackney. If we pretended for a second that we were living with the same population density here in the Northumberland Strait as we were in London, our number of residents would jump from 25 to 180,000. I suppose the point that number crunching illustrates, is that the island maybe look ‘small’ and remote, but its all relative.

![](/images/test/DSCF4031%203.JPG)

In fact everything feels bigger, wider, more open. The shifting of the seasons has begun, as it wobbles between a drawn out winter and a slow gradual teasing of spring. With that, I feel a desire to explore and stretch my legs, and an eagerness to spend life outdoors in gentler climes. My excitement for the coming spring is just as strong as ever, but this time it’s borne from a winter rested and nourished, rather than weathered and detested. I feel I have made peace with winter - a thing to be embraced instead of endured. It has helped having the physical and mental space to slow down, which I have found simultaneously, comforting and uncomfortable. I remember a physics friend and mentor telling me one summer that I needed to disconnect from my work and fully rest - so my brain could be in the best shape to be able to absorb new information and work hard in the new academic year. His advice was to take enough time off so that you feel not just rested, but bored. I’ve mentioned before, but I don’t really ever feel bored, there are always photos to take, books to read, new songs to learn etc. But I think I know what he means now. There is a discomfort that comes from rest, that if you rest too long you might lose part of who you are, or who you used to be. I don’t want to get too philosophical here, but this winter has given me a chance to lean into the discomfort. That way, when you come out the other side feeling recharged and motivated, it comes from a place of wanting to do something, rather than just feeling like you should.

![](/images/test/b3fad3b2-8b67-41ae-80c4-9d32b79b0222.JPG)

We have had a real taste of fluctuating Atlantic Canada spring over the last two weeks. To set the scene, on my birthday at the beginning of March we had more snow, bright sunshine and I think it was -19 degrees C (outside) when I woke up that morning to start the fire. A week later, I was sitting out on the deck in t-shirt and shorts, watching the snow around me slowly melt away. Two days later winter was back and dumped a foot of snow. But the promise of spring is well and truly in the air - the birds are singing, trees budding and small green shoots of life have appeared beneath the melting snow.

Back in mid-February we had our first winter guest, when Corinne, unable to catch her flight to Boston because of another bad snowstorm, was instead able to catch a flight to Pictou Island! She arrived on a beautifully sunny day and after taking a walk to the beach we sat outside for a couple of hours, enjoying a beer/wine. Cameron and I had both picked up a fair amount of teaching work that week, and Cameron was also busy with assignments for his masters course, but it was lovely to have the company and to have someone else to enjoy the winter olympics with. Corinne is a big sports fan, particularly hockey and curling. If you followed the Olympics in Milan this year, you will also know that both of those sports had their controversial moments in the spotlight.

And I had the joy and novelty of a Pictou Island birthday. I love my birthday - I like to make a fuss of myself but I don’t expect others to. However it’s nice to have an excuse to get together and some of my island neighbours organised an afternoon (that stretched into the evening) of ping pong, pool, snacks and nattering. I have relished getting to know the other wintering households and I’ve been made to feel so warm and welcome. Part of what excites me most about the coming spring is bringing our island socialising into the outdoors, into the sunshine a bit more - although we have spent a few sunny afternoons outdoors around the fire. We’re not there just yet though - and we had started to run low on wood. What with winter hitting so early and so strong, and with Cam and I learning the efficiency sweet spots of heating an old farmhouse, our supply dwindled. Of course the news spread fast among the other residents and before we knew it three of our neighbours had popped by to assess the situation and offer help. So last Sunday we spent a few hours chopping up some wood our neighbour had spare, involving two more neighbours with chainsaws and one with a wood splitter. The wood was loaded up and then dumped right next to the barn - enough to keep us going until the spring really kicks in. Of course the small army of helpers needed feeding so I knocked up the biggest batch of ragu/bolognaise I could manage. I hope we will be able to return the favour if our neighbours are in need. It is an amazing community in that respect - before you even know you need help, the offer is there. No one on the island will go without.
